<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="264" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1329]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,871,896]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is a noun in apposition taken from the 
<typeStatus box="[1019,1067,872,896]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">type</typeStatus>
locality, where, for a long time, several studies on Uruguayan wolf spiders have been developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1329]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,400,943,968]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">Natural History.</emphasis>
Several behavioural and ecological studies were developed on this species, which was identified as 
<taxonomicName box="[298,491,980,1005]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Allocosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alticeps">
<emphasis box="[298,491,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">Allocosa alticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[507,716,980,1005]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Allocosa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marindia" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[507,716,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">Allocosa marindia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[724,815,980,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[724,815,980,1005]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is simpatric and synchronic with 
<emphasis box="[1201,1302,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">
<taxonomicName box="[1201,1298,980,1004]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Glieschiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">A. senex</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but present developmental and behavioural differences that result in reproductive isolation from the other species (
<bibRefCitation author="Costa" box="[1300,1431,1015,1040]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" refString="Costa, F. G. (1995) Ecologia y actividad diaria de las aranas de la arena Allocosa spp. (Araneae, Lycosidae) en Marindia, localidad costera del sur del Uruguay. Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 55, 457 - 466." type="journal article" year="1995">Costa 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Costa" box="[151,345,1052,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" refString="Costa, F. G., Simo, M. &amp; Aisenberg, A. (2006) Composicion y ecologia de la fauna epigea de Marindia (Canelones, Uruguay) con especial enfasis en las aranas: un estudio de dos anos con trampas de intercepcion. In: Menafra, R., Rodriguez- Gallego, L., Scarabino, F. &amp; Conde, D. (Eds.), Bases para la conservacion y el manejo de la costa uruguaya. Vida Silvestre Uruguay, Montevideo, pp 427 - 436." type="book chapter" year="2006">
Costa 
<emphasis box="[221,278,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
). Females and males construct burrows in the sand and the species show sex roles and sexual size dimorphism reversal (
<bibRefCitation author="Aisenberg" box="[396,678,1087,1112]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" refString="Aisenberg, A. &amp; Costa, F. G. (2008) Reproductive isolation and sex role reversal in two sympatric sand-dwelling wolf spiders of the genus Allocosa. Canadian Journal of Zoology, 7, 648 - 658. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1139 / Z 08 - 040" type="journal article" year="2008">Aisenberg &amp; Costa 2008</bibRefCitation>
; Aisenberg &amp; González 2011; 
<bibRefCitation author="Aisenberg" box="[1022,1203,1087,1112]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" refString="Aisenberg, A. (2014) Adventurous females and demanding males: sex role reversal in a Neotropical spider. In: Macedo, R. &amp; Machado, G. (Eds.), Sexual selection: perspectives and models from the Neotropics. Elsevier, Amsterdam, pp. 163 - 182." type="book chapter" year="2014">Aisenberg 2014</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Lerette" box="[1215,1425,1087,1112]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" refString="Lerette, S., Aisenberg, A., Costa, F. G., Sotelo-Silveira, J. R. &amp; Bidegaray, L. (2015) Deteccion de la bacteria endosimbionte Wolbachia en la arana lobo Allocosa alticeps y posibles efectos sobre la proporcion sexual. Boletin de la Sociedad Zoologica del Uruguay, 24 (2), 171 - 177." type="journal article" year="2015">
Lerette 
<emphasis box="[1300,1356,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). As reported for 
<taxonomicName box="[332,427,1124,1148]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Glieschiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis box="[332,427,1124,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">A. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, males produce volatile pheromones (
<bibRefCitation author="Aisenberg" box="[859,1120,1124,1149]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" refString="Aisenberg, A., Baruffaldi, L. &amp; Gonzalez, M. (2010 a) Behavioural evidence of male volatile pheromones in the sex role reversed wolf spiders Allocosa brasiliensis and Allocosa alticeps. Naturwissenschaften, 97, 63 - 70. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00114 - 009 - 0612 - z" type="journal article" year="2010" yearSuffix="a">
Aisenberg 
<emphasis box="[984,1042,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">et al.</emphasis>
2010a
</bibRefCitation>
) and sexual dimorphism on chelicerae, forelegs and palpal traits has been reported (
<bibRefCitation author="Aisenberg" box="[785,1051,1159,1184]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" refString="Aisenberg, A., Costa, F. G., Gonzalez, M., Postiglioni, R. &amp; Perez-Miles, F. (2010 b) Sexual dimorphism in chelicerae, forelegs and palpal traits in two burrowing wolf spider (Araneae: Lycosidae) with sex-role reversal. Journal of Natural History, 44, 1189 - 1202. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222931003632716" type="journal article" year="2010" yearSuffix="b">
Aisenberg 
<emphasis box="[910,968,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">et al.</emphasis>
2010b
</bibRefCitation>
). The species lives in sandy coast (Costa 2014; 
<bibRefCitation author="Costa" box="[304,533,1196,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" refString="Costa, F. G. &amp; Simo, M. (2014) Fenologia de las aranas epigeas de una zona costera del sur de Uruguay: un estudio bianual con trampas de caida. Boletin de la Sociedad Zoologica del Uruguay, 23 (1), 1 - 15." type="journal article" year="2014">Costa &amp; Simó 2014</bibRefCitation>
; Aisenberg 
<emphasis box="[668,726,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">et al.</emphasis>
2011b) and is mainly found in areas more densely covered by psammophile vegetation, compared to 
<taxonomicName box="[594,690,1232,1256]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Glieschiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis box="[594,690,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">A. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(M. Simó, pers. obs.). The diet is varied, including mainly other spiders, Diptera and 
<taxonomicName box="[382,534,1269,1293]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hymenoptera</taxonomicName>
and predation by 
<taxonomicName box="[737,831,1268,1292]" class="Arachnida" family="Lycosidae" genus="Glieschiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis box="[737,831,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">A. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported (
<bibRefCitation author="Aisenberg" box="[996,1243,1268,1293]" pageId="3" pageNumber="264" refString="Aisenberg, A., Gonzalez, M., Laborda, A., Postiglioni, R. &amp; Simo, M. (2009) Reversed cannibalism, foraging, and surface activities of Allocosa alticeps and Allocosa brasiliensis: two wolf spiders from coastal sand dunes. Journal of Arachnology, 37, 135 - 138. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1636 / T 08 - 52.1" type="journal article" year="2009">
Aisenberg 
<emphasis box="[1119,1175,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="264">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
